The paper focuses on the development of a robotic system for assistive purposes, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The system is designed to be intuitive and easy for a human user to interact with, which involves aspects of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The system uses gaze tracking to decode the user's intentions, which involves computer vision (cs.CV) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) techniques. The implementation of action sequences through the system involves decision making and control, which could fall under machine learning (cs.LG).
